Spectacular "wingsuit" jump over Bogota
Sportsman Jhonathan Florez jumped Thursday from a helicopter over Bogota, the Colombian capital.
Equipped with a wingsuit (a combination with wings), it passed 160 km/h above the famous Monserrate shrine, located at more than 3,000 meters above sea level, where many bad guys had gathered to observe its feat.
A black box in your car?
While planners in the U.S. road network are struggling to find the money to repair the deprecated highway infrastructure, many are looking for a solution in the form of a small black box that attaches itself to the dashboard of your car.
The aircraft, which record all the miles travelled by a motorist and transmit the information to the officials, are at the centre of a controversial attempt in Washington and in the planning government offices to redesign the obsolete system of financing the main American roads.
The generally uninteresting sector of major axis planning suddenly led to a lively debate and heated alliances.
The libertarians have joined environmental groups to lobby for the government to use the small boxes to keep track of the miles you travel, and possibly the road you travel, and then use the information to draft a tax law.
The Tea Party is shocked.
The American Civil Liberties Union is also very concerned and expresses concern about the protection of privacy.
And while members of Congress are unable to agree whether to continue, several states have not waited.
They are looking at how, over the next decade, they will be able to switch to a system that allows drivers to pay according to the number of miles travelled.
Thousands of motorists have already embarked these black boxes, sometimes equipped with a GPS monitoring system, for an experimental trip.
This is truly indispensable for our nation.
"It's not like we have a choice," said Hasan Ikhrata, executive director of the Southern California Association of Governments, who predicts that the state will begin recording the miles travelled by each Californian motorist by 2025.
There's going to be a change in the way we pay these taxes.
The technology is there to do it.
The pressure comes from the fact that the country's Highway Trust Fund, financed with taxes that the Americans pay at the pump, is financially dry.
Americans don't buy as much gas as they used to.
Cars can travel more than miles with a gallon.
The federal tax itself, which is 18.4 cents per gallon, has not increased in 20 years.
Politicians are reluctant to raise the tax, even by 1 cent, while gasoline prices are high.
"The gas tax is simply not sustainable," said Lee Munnich, a transportation policy specialist at the University of Minnesota.
His state recently installed trackers on 500 cars to test a payment system per mile.
"It turns out to be the most logical long-term alternative," he said.
Wonks calls this a mileage user fee.
It is not surprising that the idea seduces urban liberals, since taxes could be used to change driving habits so as to reduce congestion and gas emissions, for example.
California planners are interested in the system as they develop strategies to achieve the goals set out in the state's ambitious laws on global warming.
But Representative Bill Shuster (R-Pa.), Chair of the Transport Committee of the House of Representatives, said he also considered it the most viable long-term alternative.
Supporters of the Reason Foundation's free market also appreciate the idea of charging drivers per mile.
"It's not just a tax coming into a big black hole," said Adrian Moore, Vice President of Policy at Reason Foundation.
People pay more directly for the benefits they receive.
The movement is also supported by two former U.S. Transport Secretaries who, in a 2011 report, urged Congress to move towards payment per mile.
The U.S. Senate approved a $90 million pilot project last year that would have involved approximately 10,000 cars.
But the Speaker of the House killed the proposal, responding to the concerns of rural legislators representing voters who have to travel many miles every day to get to their work or to the city.
Nevertheless, several States and major cities are making progress.
The most determined is Oregon, which mobilized 5,000 drivers to lead the country's largest experience.
These motorists will soon pay the Crown kilometric fees instead of gasoline taxes.
Nevada has already completed a pilot project.
The city of New York is considering one.
Illinois is testing a limited number of trucks.
And coalition I-95, which includes 17 agencies involved in road transport in states along the U.S. east coast (including Maryland, Pennsylvania, Virginia and Florida), is exploring how it could implement change.
The concept is not a universal success.
In Nevada, where about 50 volunteer motorists recently equipped their car with an aircraft, drivers were worried that the government could follow their every move.
"Anxiety about Big Brother and this kind of thing is a big problem," said Alauddin Khan, who leads the strategic performance management in Nevada's Department of Transportation.
It's not something people want.
At the beginning of the trial, the Nevada ACLU warned on its site: "It would be relatively easy to turn these devices into full-fledged location devices."
It is not necessary to build a huge and cumbersome technological infrastructure that will inevitably be expanded to keep records of people's daily goings and goings.
Nevada is one of the few states that are now struggling to find affordable technology that would allow the state to know how many miles a car travels, but without knowing the exact location or time.
If we can do that, Khan added, citizens will be more comfortable.
Researching this technology has led some state agencies to use a small California startup named True Mileage.
Initially, the company was not intended to assist motorists who pay taxes to the states.
It sought to break into the emerging auto insurance market, where drivers would pay based on their mileage.
But the devices that it tests have pleased the planners of the major axes because they do not use GPS and provide a limited amount of information, periodically downloaded by modem.
"People will be more inclined to do this if you don't record their speed and locate them," said Ryan Morrison, Managing Director of True Mileage.
Big mistakes have been made in the pilot programmes of some States.
There are much cheaper ways and far less intrusive methods of doing so.
In Oregon, planners try the experiment by offering motorists different choices.
They can choose a device with or without GPS.
They can still choose not to have a device at all, preferring instead to pay a package based on the average number of miles travelled by all state residents.
Other states hope to sell the concept to distrustful citizens by allowing devices to do more, rather than not enough.
In New York City, transport officials are looking to develop a tax system that would also be equipped to pay parking fees, provide "driving payment" insurance and create a real-time speed data set from other drivers that motorists could use to avoid traffic jams.
"Car drivers would be encouraged to participate because of the benefits that the system offers them," said a document on urban development.
However, some transport planners wonder whether the whole debate on the payment per mile is simply a huge diversion.
At the Metropolitan Transportation Commission of the San Francisco Bay Area, officials say Congress could very simply manage the bankruptcy of the Highway Trust Fund by increasing gas taxes.
An additional one-time or annual tax could be imposed on hybrid drivers and others whose vehicles do not consume a lot of gasoline, so that everyone pays their fair share.
"There is no need for radical surgery when you simply need aspirin," said Randy Rentschler, Director of Legislation and Public Affairs at the Commission.
If we do that, hundreds of millions of motorists will worry about protecting their privacy and a lot of other things.
David Bowie: Four New Listening
The English musician hasn't finished surprising this year.
Starting with The Next Day, released in January, it concocted a luxury re-release scheduled for November 4, with several new releases.
Four have already emerged on the Web.
The announcement of the release of a new album by David Bowie had left everyone panicky.
On his 66th birthday, January 8, 2013, he declared that a new album would be released in March.
After ten years of silence (the last record, Reality, dates from 2003) and too few public appearances, the English musician proved that he could still be counted on to sparkle the pop scene.
A feast for his fans
Not tired of surprises, David Bowie had more than one ride in his bag with The Next Day.
The Thin White Duke has planned to reissue this album on November 4.
For the occasion, he concocted a real feast for his fans.
This reissue, entitled The Next Day Extra, will be presented in the form of three discs: the original album, unreleased studio sessions and remixes, as well as a DVD containing the four clips already unveiled.
The Next Day Extra will contain a total of ten additional tracks compared to the original album: the three tracks of the Deluxe edition, five songs specially unveiled for the occasion, as well as two remixes.
David Bowie made the presentations of this beautiful box in a video.
He introduces both each of the discs, but also the accessories provided with: exclusive photos and pouches, a notebook to share his own impressions, a booklet with the lyrics...
And, above all, he gives a taste of his new Atomica title, typically in the vein of The Next Day, with very forward guitars and skilfully controlled rock electricity.
New ones already on the list
But Atomica is not the only title to reveal its charms.
The Informer, Like A Rocket Man, Born In A UFO are also available on the Web.
The Informer is double-sided: a disturbing intro before a light cavalcade that gradually slows down to give way to a pop ballad.
On Like A Rocket Man, did Bowie want to make a little reference to Elton John's Rocket Man or even Gravity?
With this playful title, the singer seems in any case in his element when he no longer has his feet on the ground.
Space Oddity, next door, was much more serious.
On Born In A UFO, David Bowie once again refers to his strangeness: would it come from another planet?
Guitar riffs, bewitching, make you want to leave Earth.
Bowie is in any case having fun playing chameleon with these titles: informer turn, man aboard a rocket, Martian potential...
He hides and reveals at the same time, plays to adopt different personalities, as he has done throughout his career, notably with his characters Ziggy Stardust and Aladdin Sane.
It is no wonder that he has a mask in his hand in the photograph of the L'Invitation au Voyage campaign, by Louis Vuitton, whose new face he embodies.
It will appear in one of their commercials, broadcast from November 10.
Defence Minister Rob Nicholson insisted that injured soldiers were not summarily released from the Canadian Armed Forces, and stressed that a transition process was being followed by all soldiers before they returned to civilian life.
Attacked by the Liberals and New Democrats in the House of Commons, Mr. Nicholson assured that before their release, members of the army were following a transition plan in collaboration with their superiors.
All wounded soldiers receive appropriate care for their return to civilian life and none of them are released until they are ready, he said.
Detractors accuse the government of wanting to save money by not allowing injured members - who do not meet the "universal service" rule of the army requiring staff to be able to perform a variety of tasks - to reach the 10-year eligibility period required for pension benefits.
They cited two cases reported by La Presse Canadienne, including that of a soldier released last Friday.
Corporal David Hawkins, a reservist from London, Ontario, suffering from post-traumatic stress disorder, was released from the military despite his request to remain for another year in order to receive a fully indexed retirement.
His case followed that of Corporal Glen Kirkland, who stated before a parliamentary committee last month that he had been pushed out before being ready because he did not meet the universality of service rule.
Mr. Hawkins pointed out that a soldier could be prepared to leave, with plans and consultation sessions, but that it was totally different than wanting to leave the ranks.
"I told them I wasn't ready," he said in an interview with La Presse Canadienne on Wednesday.
I asked for months if there was a way for me to stay, and they said no.
Since the beginning of major fighting in Afghanistan, the army has struggled to determine what latitude it can give to wounded soldiers who want to remain in the ranks, but who are not fit for combat.
Under the current rules, seriously injured soldiers have up to three years to recover.
If they do not meet the criteria for deployment abroad, they may be forced to leave the army.
Data presented to Parliament last year indicate that of the 1,218 soldiers released for medical reasons, 199 had not reached the required length of service to obtain pension benefits.
The Liberal veteran spokesman, Jim Karygiannis, on Wednesday called for the reinstatement of Corporal Hawkins, while NDP Jack Harris called for the immediate end of "this shameful practice."
Disney bets on tablets to launch an animated series
The American media and entertainment group Disney has decided to focus on tablets on its own television channels for the upcoming release of a new children's series.
The first nine episodes of Sheriff Callie's Wild West will be available from November 24 on watchdisneyjunior.com or via its mobile and tablet app.
Its global launch on Disney's channels is not expected until 2014, details the press release of its Disney Junior division.
The cartoon, intended for children from 2 to 7 years old, tells the adventures of the pussy Callie, sheriff of a city in the American west where she makes order with a magic lasso.
Each episode includes two 11-minute stories.
"Interacting with smartphones and tablets is a second nature for children today," commented Albert Cheng, Vice President for Digital Products at Disney/ABC Television Group, quoted in the press release.
This type of experience is part of Disney's efforts to "extend the life of its series and build new relationships with its audience through increasingly important digital platforms," he added.
A survey published earlier this week by Common Sense Media showed an explosion in the use of mobile devices by young children in the United States: 38% of children under 2 years of age have already used a tablet or phone, and 72% of children under 8 years of age, compared to 10% and 38% respectively two years ago.
Snowden is ready to "cooperate" with Germany on the issue of US surveillance
Edward Snowden, the U.S. intelligence whistleblower, said he was willing to go to Berlin to testify before the German parliament if the U.S. National Security Agency and its director Keith Alexander did not provide answers on their activities.
German MP Hans-Christian Ströbele met Mr Snowden in Russia on Thursday, where he enjoys the right of asylum, to discuss his testimony in Germany.
In a letter that the MP presented to the media in Berlin on Friday, Mr Snowden said: "Although the result of my efforts was obviously positive, my government continues to treat the difference of opinion as a flight and seeks to penalise political discourse with accusations against which it is impossible to defend itself."
However, telling the truth is not a crime.
In his letter, Mr. Snowden wrote that he believed that the support of the international community could persuade the U.S. government to drop the criminal charges against him.
As part of the complaint filed by the U.S. Department of Justice, he is charged with espionage and theft of state property.
Hans-Peter Friedrich, German Interior Minister, told the Zeit Online: "If Mr Snowden is ready to talk to German officials, we will make this possible."
Relations between the United States and Germany have been put to a severe test by complaints that the NSA had tapped the mobile phone of German Chancellor Angela Merkel.
Thomas Oppermann, the deputy who heads the parliamentary group overseeing the foreign secret services, said that if there was a chance to hear Mr. Snowden as a witness "without endangering him and completely ruining relations with the United States", it should be taken advantage of.
Mr Ströbele, German Green MEP, posted a photo of him with Mr Snowden on his Twitter account.
During his visit to Russia, he was accompanied by two German journalists.
Mr. Ströbele stated that, according to the lawyer for the former NSA consultant, Mr. Snowden could not return to Russia if he left the country.
If Mr Snowden were to testify in Germany, he would have to be assured that he would be "safe" there, the MP said.
Mr. Snowden wrote in his letter that he had been subjected to a "serious and sustained" campaign of persecution that forced him to leave his country.
However, he said that he had been encouraged by the global response to “my act of political expression”.
Citizens around the world, as well as senior officials – including in the United States – have found the revelation of an inexplicable system of permanent surveillance to be of public benefit.
The letter puts forward an offer of cooperation with the German authorities "when the difficulties of this humanitarian situation have been resolved".
Cogeco Cable could soon offer interactive TV
Cogeco Cable subscribers may well have access to applications such as Facebook, Twitter and ultimately Netflix video-on-demand service via their television in a future that does not seem so distant.
The Cogeco subsidiary said on Thursday that it is currently conducting preliminary tests of the beta version of this platform with some of its users.
"This will allow us to highlight more user-friendly interfaces as well as more options," explained Cogeco President and CEO Louis Audet in an interview.
Cogeco Cable is thus following in the footsteps of its competitors, such as Bell, even though Cogeco's subsidiary does not yet have a specific date for this new platform.
"We need to adapt and change or resist change and fail," said Audet.
The ultimate goal remains to provide tools that our clients currently do not have access to.
The telecommunications giant Rogers has already indicated that it could offer Netflix if certain technical details, which have not been cited, could be resolved.
In the United States, the popular video service says it is in discussions with some major cable companies to make its service available through their broadcast platforms.
Cogeco and Cogeco Cable also welcomed the announcement made by the Harper Government in its Speech from the Throne on October 16.
Ottawa wants to force cable and satellite television providers to offer customers the option of paying for pay-per-view services.
"It's been about two and a half years since we said that the idea of forcing consumers to buy large chain packages doesn't work," said Audet.
He hoped, however, that the consultations conducted by the Canadian Radio-television and Telecommunications Commission (CRTC) would lead to interesting recommendations.
"A new kind of framework will have to emerge from these discussions to define our new Canadian cultural policy on television," said Cogeco's CEO.
The CRTC has been consulting with the public since last week and is expected to continue with the industry next spring.
In terms of results, Cogeco reported a net profit of $43.8 million in the fourth quarter, or 82¢ per share.
This is a decrease from net earnings of $44.9 million, or 83¢ per share, for the same period last year.
The Montreal-based company explains this decline through depreciation costs related to new acquisitions.
Cogeco acquired the US-based Atlantic Broadband cable company for $1.36 billion in 2012.
This was the first major acquisition of the company after the one that failed in Portugal.
Last December, the Montreal-based company also purchased Peer 1 Network Entreprises, an Internet provider based in Vancouver, for $526 million.
As for Cogeco's revenues, they grew by 41.5% in the fourth quarter to reach 504.7 million.
They are $1.8 billion for the current fiscal year.
The net profit of its main subsidiary, Cogeco Cable, was 43.9 million, or 90¢ per share, down from 45.7 million, or 93¢ per share, in the same period last year.
However, Cogeco Cable's revenues increased by 45% to 470.4 million.
The company lost 15,237 customers in the fourth quarter.
However, in fiscal 2013, Cogeco Cable's number of customers increased 5,546.
Mr. Audet is not worried that the number of clients will fluctuate in this way.
For me, this is not an indication of a change in trend, he observed.
It varies from one quarter to the next with very strong competition.
Horse in beef products
Horse meat was detected in canned beef products, sold by two small UK retail outlets at low prices, today announced the agency responsible for food hygiene.
Routine tests revealed that the products, developed in January in Romania and sold by the Home Bargains and Quality Save chains, contained horse DNA at a height of 1 to 5%.
"Since horse meat is not mentioned in the list of ingredients, it should not have been present in the product," explained the UK agency.
A scandal about the presence of horse meat in cooked dishes broke out in Europe at the beginning of the year, following tests carried out in Ireland.
According to reviews by the European Commission, France was the country most affected by the presence of this type of meat in products intended to contain only beef.
A collision between two vehicles resulted in four injuries, early Friday, on Highway 131, in Lanaudière.
Shortly before 4 a.m., a motorist driving in a northerly direction at Saint-Félix-de-Valois lost control of his vehicle and struck a car coming in the other direction.
The four occupants of the two vehicles were injured, but there was no fear for their lives.
Traffic had returned to normal around 6:00 a.m. on Friday.
Frontier Airlines plans to charge for carry-on baggage
Frontier Airlines plans to charge up to $100 for passengers carrying carry-on baggage on its flights.
Frontier Airlines plans to start charging up to $100 for carry-on baggage and $2 for coffee or soda, although in its announcement on Wednesday, it indicated that passengers could take the unopened can with them as the aircraft descends.
New hand luggage charges apply to bags stored in the upper compartment, so small bags installed under the seat will always be free of charge.
Frontier stated that it would charge $25 if the fees were paid in advance and $100 if the travellers only paid once at the gate.
Frontier's spokesperson, Kate O'Malley, indicated that the $100 was intended to encourage travellers to pay the fees in advance.
"We don't want to make this price pay," she explained.
The airlines started charging for the first and second checked baggage in 2008.
Passengers who tried to avoid this expense put as much as they could in the carry-on baggage stored in the upper compartments, so there was often no room in those compartments.
These fees are a way to ensure that passengers carry fewer things on board.
O'Malley said these new fees will not really be used to raise money.
The aim is to make the most loyal Frontier customers understand that it is becoming increasingly difficult to find room in the upper compartments.
Passengers who purchase their tickets on the airline's website will not have to pay.
For example, a passenger queued at a Frontier boarding gate could carry a bag for free, while the next person in the queue could have to pay $100 for a similar bag.
O'Malley explained that Frontier's site and check-in procedures are changing to ensure that passengers are aware of these fees before arriving at the door.
Frontier's hand baggage charges will not be applied until the summer, although no date has been set.
Passengers often frown about baggage and other expenses, but airlines love them.
They consider that baggage handling costs are significant and that passengers who want this service should pay for it.
Many people on Wall Street view the addition of baggage charges as a sign that airlines charge enough to cover the cost of air travel after years of loss.
However, many of them did not cover the cost of baggage.
Spirit Airlines Inc. had applied the first carry-on baggage charges three years ago, and the low-cost Allegiant company followed a little later.
The only other company imposing such charges is the Hungarian company Wizz Air, said the consultant to airlines Jay Sorensen, who closely follows the surcharges.
In a December 2011 report, he estimated that Spirit's carry-on baggage costs were $50 million per year.
Sorensen, a former manager of Midwest Airlines, recently travelled on Spirit and wondered what he would find at the boarding gate as passengers discovered the company's unusual hand baggage charges.
"I've never seen such a smooth boarding procedure in my entire professional career," he said.
I expected to see teeth gnashing and a fight breaking out at the door.
The aircraft was full, he added, "the passengers boarded at the speed of lightning."
Frontier also makes like Spirit and charges a $2 fee for coffee, tea, soda or fruit juice.
Frontier indicated that passengers who take a soda or juice can take the unopened can with them, and those who take coffee can be served free of charge.
It will always distribute water free of charge.
US Airways briefly attempted to charge for drinks in 2008 but went back seven months after the passengers complained and while no other major airline had followed.
Frontier's decision to charge for carry-on baggage when passengers do not purchase their tickets directly from the airline is its last effort to encourage customers to visit its site.
Airlines pay online travel vendors like Orbitz $10 to $25 for each ticket sold.
This has prompted all airlines to encourage passengers to buy directly from them instead of going to an online travel agency.
However, Frontier has gone further in this area.
In September, it began to offer only half a mile of loyalty to customers who purchased their tickets via an online travel agency.
On Wednesday, she reduced mile bonuses by 25% on a trip.
For example, a 1,000-mile Frontier trip purchased from an online travel agency would save 250 miles.
It also allows passengers to choose their seat in advance only if they buy their ticket directly from the Frontier website.
Frontier has a loyal clientele in its home town, Denver, but its business is shrinking and it is losing money.
Revenues dropped by 9% and its flight capacity decreased by almost 13% in the first quarter, according to financial results released on Wednesday by its parent company, Republic Airways Holdings Inc.
Republic tried to correct Frontier's finances by selling the airline.
NSA calls into question an "internal error" and not hackers for the breakdown of its site
The National Security Agency working in the shadows said on Friday that it was a bug that caused the breakdown of its public website for a few hours, not hackers as some had claimed online.
"NSA.gov remained inaccessible for a few hours tonight due to an internal error that occurred during a scheduled update," the spy agency said in an email statement.
The problem will be solved tonight.
The allegations that the breakdown was due to a distributed denial of service attack [DSD] are false.
Earlier tonight, online server trackers noted that the NSA site had been down for at least 6 hours, and some users still cannot access the site.
Earlier, an NSA spokesperson told ABC News that the agency's sensitive internal network was "not at all" compromised.
No classified information is in danger, the spokesperson explained.
At least one group of online hacktivists claimed to be responsible for the breakdown of the NSA site by a DSD attack.
DSD attacks aim to flood a targeted site until the servers are overloaded and the site collapses.
Cyber-tactics is not very sophisticated and the attacks are not intended to penetrate the internal network of the target system.
The NSA, once known as the "No Such Agency", has come under the spotlight and has been heavily criticized in recent months as a result of a wave of revelations about its extensive national and international communications monitoring programs – which are part of the NSA's secret files stolen from the agency and disclosed by NSA's former disillusioned consultant, Edward Snowden.
This growing controversy around the agency has led to many speculations that tonight's incident was the result of a targeted cyber-operation.
Delta Downtown now closed
The Delta Centre-Ville hotel closed on Thursday in Montreal, after 36 years of existence.
The investment fund that owned the building sold it to developers who will turn it into student residences.
Three hundred and fifty people worked at the hotel.
Of these, 200 have still not found a new job.
Delta promises not to let down its employees.
Employers came to meet with employees directly on site, employees were met individually to assess their needs.
"This support will continue for the next six months," explains Delta Hotels Regional Director of Labour Relations, Félix Bisson.
The closure of the Delta is taking place in a very competitive hotel market.
The investment fund that owned this building had choices to make.
Either he was reinvesting in the building to continue operating it, so there were investments of tens of millions while the competition is very fierce, there are many new hotels that appeared in Montreal.
"Or he was selling it to someone else and that's what happened," explains Paul Arsenault, Chair of Transat Tourism at the UQAM School of Management Sciences.
Other hotels in Montreal will also be converted in the coming months, such as Crown Plaza, which will become a residence for seniors.
Meanwhile, four hotel projects totalling nearly 600 rooms will be created within two years.
For Titan's CEO, "Goodyear Amiens' buying project starts with zero employees"
After tossing the towel in January for the partial takeover of Amiens-Nord's Goodyear site promised at the closure, Maurice Taylor, CEO of the American tyre manufacturer Titan, says today, ready to save 333 jobs out of the 1,137 that the plant has.
Arnaud Montebourg, Minister for Productive Recovery, had already announced this on Monday 21 October.
After giving up the plan to buy the plant in January, you come back today.
You had pronounced violent attacks and insults, speaking of "so-called workers", who "work three hours" a day, of "mad" unions, targeting the CGT.
We don't understand that volte-face.
Is it to please Mr Montebourg?
I'm not trying to please anyone.
Except for my wife.
Mr Montebourg, is a charming young man who is trying to save some of the best paid industrial jobs.
If I hurt someone with my words, I'm sorry.
But France also has a high level of tax and unemployment.
Does the truth hurt you?
Working seven hours a day when in other countries we work eight hours handicaps France.
In India, China and many other countries, we work ten to twelve hours a day.
But I have no prejudices about France.
What I see is a factory that manufactures good agricultural tires, has good equipment, is well located and has space to expand.
Why does Titan need this factory so much?
Titan doesn't need to buy this factory.
But with a fair price and skilled workers, it's worth a try.
What kind of deal do you expect between the CGT and Goodyear?
If, since the announcement of the plant's closure, Goodyear had offered employees a good severance pay, I think 100% of the employees would have accepted it.
Now, let's imagine that Titan buys Goodyear's closed plant.
As a result, Titan could move the machines to Poland or to any other country in the European Union that still has its own currency.
I think Mr Montebourg knows that.
But he wants to keep the Amiens factory with at least 333 well-paid jobs.
Titan agrees to recruit them from among the approximately 1,200 current Goodyear employees.
So Mr. Montebourg needs a commitment from Titan before he tries to get the CGT to sit at the table with Goodyear.
The first step is that the CGT and Goodyear seal an agreement on severance benefits for all employees.
As a result, there will be no more employees in the factory.
Mr Montebourg said you were ready to guarantee these 333 jobs for four years.
Do you confirm that?
The only number I mentioned to the minister was 333.
I know he'd like a four-year guarantee.
But, as I told you, the CGT and Goodyear must first agree on severance benefits.
If all employees accept them, the plant's purchase plan starts with zero employees.
How can we give guarantees of duration of employment when there are no more employees left on the site?
If Mr. Montebourg succeeds in reaching agreement between the CGT and Goodyear and Titan buys the plant, we intend to stay in Amiens-Nord for more than four years.
Bombardier's profit declines, while aircraft deliveries and orders decline
Bombardier Inc., a Canadian aircraft and rail manufacturer, reported a 15% drop in net earnings on Thursday, under pressure from lower orders and deliveries of aircraft during the third quarter and from contract problems in its Trains division.
Bombardier, based in Montreal, also did not provide in-flight test data for its brand new CSeries aircraft or information on whether the aircraft will meet its ambitious commercial commissioning schedule by September.
After the pilot's inaugural flight about a month and a half ago, the pilot flew only three times, and the question then arose as to whether the test phase was on track.
The results were not up to expectations and the share price fell by 8% on the Toronto Stock Exchange.
Cameron Doerksen, an analyst at National Bank Financial, lowered his rating Thursday from "overperformance" to "sector performance" due to the low potential for the stock exchange to increase in the next quarter or two.
"Although the decline in aircraft deliveries was largely anticipated, we are really disappointed by the profit margin in the Transport division," Cameron Doerksen said in a customer note.
We expect Bombardier to record new orders for its CSeries aircraft as the flight test program progresses.
However, if no new orders are announced in the coming months, we expect the market to become more sceptical about the program.
Bombardier hopes that the CSeries family of aircraft will be able to catapult it in the lower segment of a market now dominated by Boeing and Airbus.
The first test aircraft was unveiled in March and flew away for the first time in September after months of delay.
But the number of firm orders for CSeries aircraft is so far modest to 177. Potential buyers appear to be waiting for the results of the flight tests to validate the company's assertions about the energy efficiency and savings potential of the new airliner.
Currently, the company has registered a total of 403 purchase orders and commitments with 15 customers and operators.
Pierre Beaudoin, President and Chief Executive Officer, is confident that Bombardier will reach its target of 300 firm orders prior to the commercial launch of the first aircraft.
Leaders also reassured analysts and the media on Thursday that the program was progressing according to schedule.
"The test aircraft did not stay on the ground any longer than expected," said Mr. Beaudoin at a conference call, adding that ground tests and software updates were planned during the aircraft's downtime.
Each manufacturer plans differently.
We decided to make a first flight and provide for an update period, and that's what we did.
This will happen again throughout the flight program.
The second of the five test aircraft is expected to fly away in the coming weeks, while the others will follow shortly thereafter, the company said.
Yet analysts are skeptical that the first customer can fly a CSeries aircraft only 12 months after its inaugural flight.
