Is the European elite ready to do business with Britain?
The Business for Britain campaign was launched in April with the promise of bringing companies together and defining what wealth and job creators want to see change in our relationship with the EU.
To this end, we commissioned the largest and most comprehensive survey of UK business leaders and asked them what they thought of Britain, business and the EU.
YouGov interviewed more than 1 000 entrepreneurs, representing all sizes of companies, sectors and regions of Great Britain.
The findings of the survey will be a surprise to many.
We have discovered that the vast majority of companies are now seeking to export outside Europe, focusing on countries that are modernising and developing while EU states are stagnating.
They want the government to give priority to new trade links with countries such as China, India and Brazil rather than getting bogged down in the long and arduous process of reforming Europe's institutional arcanes.
When asked about specific policy issues – ranging from monopoly regulation to product laws – the majority of entrepreneurs believe that control over these key competencies should return to Westminster.
The single market has caused general dissatisfaction, with companies saying that the cost of the Brussels regulation is disproportionate to the benefits of being part of the European trading area – 40% of large companies, traditionally the most pro-European ones, even agree.
Finally, and more importantly, our survey of business leaders revealed that a large majority wanted Britain to pursue initiatives to change the Treaty and develop a trade-based, not policy-based, relationship with the EU.
This conclusion, which is found in all major groups and companies of all sizes, shows that the business world is insisting on a "significant change" that restores power to the UK.
The stakes are high – achieving a change in the treaty and better representing Britain's interests would see a 16% shift in votes in favour of keeping the country in the EU in a referendum.
The Prime Minister should not doubt for a moment: this survey shows that British companies support this plan to renegotiate the terms of Britain's accession to the EU.
