Scientists have just highlighted how a dog's tail movements are related to his mood.
Previous studies had shown that happy dogs moved their tails more to the right (from the dog's point of view), while nervous dogs moved them more to the left.
But now scientists say that dogs can detect and respond to these subtle differences.
Professor Georgio Vallortigara, a neuroscientist at the University of Trento, said: "Everyone knows that in man, the left and right sides of the brain are involved differently in stimuli that arouse positive or negative emotions."
Here, we tried to see what was going on in other species.
He added that just as in man, in dogs the right side of the brain was responsible for movement to the left and vice versa, and that the two hemispheres played a different role in emotions.
To learn more about how dogs respond to the disordered tail movements of other dogs, researchers followed animals watching movies featuring other dogs.
They measured the heart rate of the animals and analyzed their behaviour.
Surely it won't take long before we understand why their tails sometimes go on one side and sometimes on the other.
Professor Vallortigara explained: "We presented to dogs films featuring other dogs – either a naturalistic version or a silhouette to avoid any other confounding factor – and we were able to tamper with the movement of the tail and present it as going more to the left or right."
When the animals saw an unexpressed dog moving the tail to the right (from the point of view of the dog moving the tail), they remained perfectly relaxed.
But when they spotted a tail drifting mainly to the left (again from the point of view of the dog moving the tail), their heart rate accelerated and they looked anxious.
Professor Vallortigara said that he did not think that dogs deliberately communicate with each other through these movements.
Rather, he believes that dogs know from experience what movements they should or should not worry about.
He added: "If you meet other dogs several times and notice that, most of the time, the movement of their tail to one side is associated with a more friendly attitude and that the right side leads to a less friendly attitude, you will react according to this experience."
Researchers indicate that the results could allow owners, veterinarians and trainers to better understand the emotions of their animals.
Canine Behavior John Bradshaw, visiting professor at the School of Veterinary Sciences at the University of Bristol, said this was not the first study to examine the importance of left and right in the canine species.
Last year, a team from Lincoln University discovered that the dogs turned their heads to the left when they looked at an aggressive dog and to the right when it was a happy dog.
And in another scientific study conducted by the University of Victoria in Canada, he said: "The dogs went more easily to a robot dog when its tail moved to the left rather than to the right, instead of becoming anxious – the opposite of what appears in the Italian study."
He indicated that the differences could be due to the fact that the dogs involved in the various studies did not consider the animals of the films entirely or the robot dogs as dogs.
A study on how dogs react to real dogs could be useful, he explained.
"Although there is a lot of evidence from different mammals that both sides of the brain are being used for different purposes, many details still need to be clarified – and dogs are no exception," he said.
However, given the ease with which their behaviors can be recorded, it will certainly not take long before we understand why their tails sometimes move on one side and sometimes on the other.
