A team of biologists led by the Wildlife Conservation Society of New York has identified a new species of humpback dolphin off the northern coast of Australia.
Thibaut Bouveroux, scientific mission officer at the Observatory for the Conservation and Study of Marine Animals and Environments (OCEAMM) returns to L'Express on this discovery and explains the long process of identifying new species.
Does the discovery of this new species of humpback dolphin surprise you?
This is good news, but I am not particularly surprised.
If in the past the species have been described and identified on a morphological, anatomical and geographical basis, today, the development of new tools such as genetics allows us to improve our knowledge in the science of species classification.
It is not impossible for these advances in genetics and molecular biology to call into question the classification or membership of a species in a genus, family, or even an order.
In the early 19th century, morphologists classified animals on the basis of morphological differences between species.
Today, some of these rankings are being questioned because of advances in genetics.
Similarly, two closely morphologically related species were distinguished by genetics.
This is the case with the new species that has just been identified.
About a decade ago, the scientific community recognized two species from this subfamily: Pacific humpback dolphins and Atlantic humpback whales.
Recent analyses have identified four species.
Why is this an important discovery, as the Wildlife Conservation Society has stated?
From a conservation point of view, it is essential to know these genetic differences, in order to protect the species and thus its genetic variability.
Although this population had long been known to researchers, they did not know that it was part of a new species, present only there.
Therefore, if a problem of mass mortality caused by a viral epidemic or accidental capture arises in the region, we might be dealing with the extinction of a species, rather than with a local disappearance of a population of a species that is more widespread on Earth.
This loss of genetic heritage would be much more problematic.
A species is considered threatened or endangered based on the number of existing individuals on Earth, that is, the stock, and the potential for recovery from nearby stocks.
With respect to the Sousa chinensis species, whose population of the new species was discovered, its stock automatically became smaller, making it more vulnerable.
Why is it rare to discover new species of marine mammals?
Marine mammals are located at the top of the food chain.
They live in homogeneous, open habitats in which there are many genetic exchanges between populations and individuals.
This gene mixing limits the creation of new species.
Conversely, more closed ecosystems favour genetic isolation, which may eventually lead to the creation of new species.
It should be noted that the marine environment is the least well known.
We'd rather send robots to Mars than find out what lives in the Mariannes' pit, just 11 kilometres from the surface of the sea.
More money is spent on the search for life on other planets than on marine research, and it is high time it changed.
RBS suspends two foreign exchange traders
Royal Bank of Scotland has suspended two traders from its foreign exchange market division according to two sources close to the file, again showing that the regulators' global investigation into suspicions of currency market manipulation is beginning to bear fruit.
Some of the world's largest banks, including UBS, Barclays, Deutsche Bank and RBS, have confirmed that they are cooperating with regulators in the world's largest financial market investigations, where US$5.3 trillion is changing hands every day.
The two traders are the first RBS employees to be suspended as part of the expansion of the investigation that echoes the scandal of manipulations of the Libor interbank rate.
The bank, which refused to comment on the suspensions, confirmed this month that it had received requests for information from regulators.
"This case is still under investigation and we are cooperating fully with the CFA and other regulators," said a bank representative two weeks ago.
Last month, sources close to the file stated that RBS had sent emails and instant messages to and from a former trader to the British regulator, the Financial Conduct Authority.
This trader, Richard Usher, left RBS in 2010 and was reportedly suspended from his position as European currency spot trading manager at JPMorgan.
Rohan Ramchandani, European cash exchange trading manager at Citi, was laid off this week, while Matt Gardiner, senior currency trader at Barclays and UBS, was suspended by Standard Chartered this week.
None of these traders were charged.
Mr. Usher's file included instant messages sent to and by bankers working at Barclays and Citigroup, added sources close to the file.
UBS explained this week that it had brought an action against some of its employees after the Swiss regulator, Finma, stated that it was investigating suspicions of foreign exchange market manipulation in a number of Swiss banks.
Around the world, at least six authorities – the European Commission, Finma, the Swiss competition authority Weko, the FCA, the U.S. Department of Justice and the Hong Kong Monetary Authority – are examining allegations about bankers who have agreed to manipulate exchange market rates.
HSBC, Citigroup, JPMorgan and Crédit Suisse also launched internal investigations or received requests for information from regulators, reported sources close to the file.
Banks have been peeling instant messages and emails for years to find cases of wrongdoing.
The news about these investigations has shaken traders in a sector that has been one of the biggest growth engines of investment bank trading units in recent years, but that has been questioned this year due to low currency volatility that limits opportunities for speculators.
Some bankers have tried to minimize the case by saying that it is almost impossible to manipulate the large, highly liquid foreign exchange market, but senior traders explain that this is not necessarily true.
One senior trader said that despite the high volume of daily foreign exchange transactions, the fragmentation of liquidity between trading management platforms and the increasingly frequent use by banks of their own internal platforms "explains that it is possible to start having an impact on the market at little cost".
The news arrived the same day Credit Suisse announced that it had sent a trader working in its London Stock Exchange trading office this week after it caused a $6 million loss at the end of last year.
