Back in black and white for Marie Chouinard, who presents Danse Danse with his two new group choreographies: the first inspired by Henri Michaux's inks and poems, the second inspired by Satie's famous piano solos Gymnopedias.
An evening that allows you to see the whole prism of Chouinard, from art to tics and black of ink to white.
A white screen serves as a background wall.
On the carpet, as white, in the immense space that is the Théâtre Maisonneuve, progresses, profile, fine as a line and dressed in black, a body.
On the screen, an ink by Henri Michaux is projected.
The body, simple trait, takes its shape.
And this shape will be that of the whole room: a string of physical imitations of the drawings.
The dancers, entirely dressed in black, only the hands and face discovered, wait on each side of the playground, rush when the next graphy appears, incarnate it, come out running.
This black and white game by Henri Michaux is made in relay of solos, in group in unison (a mass that does solo), in large group of twelve solos where each performs his sign.
One thinks of "Gloire du matin", where, in solo, Chouinard performed a series of choreographic tasks written on cartels, placed online at the forefront.
It's the same principle, giant PowerPoint version.
Here, the music is strong, percussion and electric guitars.
The energy is high, the rhythm is always fast.
There will be a break when Carol Prior takes refuge under the dance mat, to deliver, microphone in hand, without sobriety or restraint, a part of Michaux' poem, monocord and monotonous in the auction, and will continue while dancing.
And the music to go back, and the sequence to resume.
This sound and energetic discharge, long, if possible, ends up deafening and numbing.
As does the regularity of the visual rhythm.
There are a few beautiful flashes - the creation of images has always been a force at Chouinard - like those hairs that are rumbling or those black fabrics that lengthen the lines.
But the choreographic approach lacks composition.
We have the impression that the choreographer, instead of going to meet the work of Michaux, has established herself, with her tics.
Result: the bodies appear flat in front of the drawings.
Michaux' inks, like Gestalt's forms, open up an imaginary wider and gibberish than dance, more porous.
Only the end, in negative, with its dancers chopped by a strobe light and white signs in a suddenly black theatre, touches magic.
The audience liked it, the welcome was warm.
The Gymnopedias, after the intermission, is richer.
The scene is partly draped with grey, the dancers and a piano are covered with fabrics, like furniture in a abandoned house.
At the piano, dancers take turns playing the scores.
Their clumsiness in music, touching, give a real fragility.
On stage, pass couples, in love duos, very sensual, even erotic.
Group work, small transition solos, moving ensembles, choirs, writing is less binary.
Buffoons appear, also familiar to Chouinard, with a red nose, in very polarized male-female romantic parades.
Loves are carnastics, runaways or players.
The gestures, the laughter and the little cries beautifully transpose the archaic, the grace and the ridiculousness of the bodies into coitus, beings that melt.
But the play takes its real flight after salvation.
A clown comes back on stage when the audience leaves.
There everything becomes permissible: the fourth wall falls, the universes explored are superimposed, the dancers rub shoulders, descend among the spectators, gloat, smoke, short-circuit, play codes of applause, spread the sauce in a cleverly calculated disorder that remains sensual.
Joy and madness permeate, and it is Chouinard's art, there, to contaminate the public.
