John Kerry pointed to a softening of the defensive attitude of the United States towards its surveillance programs by admitting, unprecedentedly, that on several occasions espionage "had gone too far inappropriately."
The Secretary of State also admitted that he, like Barack Obama, had ruled on "autopilot" when a series of incendiary revelations about NSA spying by whistleblower Edward Snowden emerged.
The leaks put the U.S. government at the centre of a diplomatic storm with its allies.
Speaking at an intergovernmental conference in London via video link, Mr Kerry said: "It is undeniable that the President, myself and other members of the government have learned of certain things in autopilot mode because we had the possibility, from the Second World War to the difficult years of the Cold War, and then of course on 11 September."
